04016nam a22005535i 9780520912182DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209121827 a10.1525/97805209121822doi  a(DE-B1597)647761  a(OCoLC)1419788549  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aBrison, Karen J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJust Talk :bGossip, Meetings, and Power in a Papua New Guinea Village /cKaren J. Brison; ed. by Karen J. Brison. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (316 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Melanesian Anthropology00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMAPS AND FIGURES -- tPLATES -- tPREFACE -- t1 Gossip and Politics -- t2 The Kwanga -- t3 Gossip, Innuendo, and Sorcery: Power without Responsibility -- t4 Village Courts and the Art of Bluffing -- t5 Getting It All Out into the Open -- t6 Rivalry and Institutionalized Duplicity: The Sociology o f Rumor -- t7 The Power of Stories -- t8 Two Models of Government -- t9 Leadership, Authority, and "Egalitarianism" -- t10 Leaders as Bad Men and Victims -- t11 Conclusions -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJust Talk examines the often overlooked role of gossip and rumor in creating power in small Melanesian communities. The Kwanga of the East Sepik Province of Papua, New Guinea think that malicious gossip is almost as dangerous as sorcery. They spend hours in community meetings, looking into rumors about sorcery, adultery, and other sources of trouble. To understand how "talk" can create and ultimately destroy the position of Melanesian leaders, Karen Brison follows discussions of particular situations over time and suggests that gossip and rumor are just as central to shaping and shifting power relations as are the public meetings which are more often studied. Kwanga community leaders build reputations by spreading rumors and dropping hints that they are confidants of sorcerers. But ultimately, the same men who build reputations through gossip and innuendo find themselves victimized in turn by malicious gossip.Just Talk suggests that our understanding of both Melanesian leadership and the power of words to construct social reality is greatly enhanced by attention to gossip and rumor: words are dangerous weapons that can have consequences the original speaker neither anticipated nor desired.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBrison, Karen J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007700340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091218240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520912182423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520912182/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles